column162: All fish and shellfish are temperature sensitive.  They follow patterns which include spawning and foraging.      For lobsters, the urge to spawn is great when they follow the slight rising temperature changes.  In the Spring, when they detect changes in water temperature, the females head inshore to molt.  After the females molt, the hard-shelled males show up to spawn.  The females harden up a bit, then it's time for the males to molt.  It is (was) almost predictable.      Now the soft females are fodder for the predators.  They arrive at about the same time as the males, Stripers & Dogs gorge them selves on the easy pickins.      Well, guess what, the same lobster cannot be caught twice.  If it's fish food, it won't get to the human's table, will it?  Oh, well maybe indirectly, Stripers are good to eat (for humans), right?

column162: who cares?  the fisheries are drastically more likely to be impacted by regulations created by non-fishermen based on insufficient data.  it seriously makes no difference.  this is like asking whether UV rays contributed to deterioration of a house that was destroyed by a tornado.  yes, it probably had an impact, but the impact was so infinitesimal as compared to the negative effects of the primary problem.
column163: if climate change reaches the fishery world on a fundamental basis, the range and annual patterns of migratory fish will change.  so the fisheries will not necessarily be impacted positively or negatively, however the specific fishery of a particular port will be impacted.  if the range of black sea bass extends northward, perhaps the virginia fishery would suffer, but the massachusetts fishery could improve.  at the same time, a new fishery in the virginia area may develop to take the place of the vacated black sea bass.  the question is not whether the fishery will be affected, but net impact on ports.  fishermen must be able to adapt, policy must allow for that adaptation.

column101: I’m not sure climate change has had a positive effect on our fishery, but the weather the last two springs has..  We catch Alewives in the spring, and water temperatures have a major effect on their behavior and intensity during the run.. If the water temp. spikes, the fish rush in a shorter period of time, some spawn too early and drop back out to sea. Despite the warm offshore water temperatures last couple years, the cold prolonged springs have kept our river temperatures from rising too fast suddenly, resulting in what appears to be a longer lasting steady run of Alewives for us, which has resulted in increased harvest numbers.
column157: I’m not sure if this is what you are asking exactly... but we sell Alewives for bait to lobstermen.. So if the lobster fishery is effected so is our ability to sell Alewives.   There are certainly forces outside the climate change discussion having negative impacts on the lobster industry, and those have impacted some of the guys we deal with.. that being said, the last 4-6 years we’ve had many of our “regular” customers setting gear later in the spring than in past years, due to cold water temperatures, and where we have such a small window of time to harvest Alewives some of them are not around to buy bait. We also see an increase of lobstermen switching to the Halibut fishery, and while they still buy Alewives for this, it’s in much smaller quantities..
column159: We have far more fish available in our location now than we did 30 years ago.. column284: If we view coastal and marine fisheries as complex social-ecological systems and/or see the blue economy as overarching social, environmental, and economic targets, we need metrics that touch upon each of these dimensions.  Metrics that are most lacking fall in the social realm, including issues related to access, equity, and distribution of benefits in fisheries.
column285: Licensed commercial fishermen speak for licensed commercial fishermen only, not “fishing communities” as a whole. Licensed commercial fishermen in federally-managed groundfisheries represent an even smaller number and less diverse grouping of participants. Fishing communities are comprised of a diversity of actors--  members of fishing families, participants across the entire fisheries value chain, those involved in ancillary, dockside services, and seafood consumers. In surveys like this, the perspectives of women, youth, minorities (foreign-born workers and immigrants), and indigenous people are excluded while the voices and needs of the most privileged and powerful, predominantly older white males within fishing communities are magnified.  A majority of participants in fisheries and members of fishing communities-- including the most vulnerable and adaptable-- are left out of surveys that simply poll licensed commercial fishermen.      For example, the tribal women and children who lost their commercial licenses because they are “not residents of Maine” won’t be able to share their thoughts. My friend B, a Cambodian refugee who runs a fishing fleet (formerly out of Portland, now out of Gloucester), will not be able to respond because while he may land over $1 million USD in fish a year, he does not read or write in English. You will not get a response from the people who pick and process shellfish, groundfish, and lobster. Nor will you hear from the wives of fishermen who are staying home to provide childcare and sell products direct to customers this summer due to the covid-19 outbreak. The unlicensed crew, deckhands, and sternmen won’t be able to respond.  And what about people who sell bait, run the wharves, run the seafood restaurants and markets, make the gear, fix the boats? What about the Asian women who fish for periwinkles and mackerel?  The unlicensed women and children who work onboard to cull and shuck shellfish?  Fish are a public resource and I am of the opinion that non-licensed community members also have a right to resources in the form of accessible, affordable, and nutritious seafood.  Do they also have a say in how we respond and adapt to climate change?      I completed this survey and shared my thoughts, but I sincerely hope it is not used for decision making purposes without the explicit acknowledgement that survey results only reflect the knowledge and opinions of a very small percentage of individuals situated within fishing communities.

I think part of that is because more fishermen are leaving traps out, and baiting them weekly, which keeps the lobsters more active. In addition, fishermen have self regulated by  punching  breeding females so they can't be harvested. column162: I don't feel that climate change is happening at the rate that has been reported. I've seen populations run a cyclical pattern, where species thrive and then decline over time based on food, habitat, and harvest. 20 years ago we could see bare ledge in shallow water, that bottom is now covered in kelp. Not because of changing water temperature, but because sea urchins aren't there to eat the kelp. Rabbit population directly relates to coyote population. I realize that isn't the ocean, but it appears to me that these changes aren't based on major global climate change, but many factors. I do agree that we have seen minimal local changes in the world. I don't feel like there has been nearly enough research of information provided to give conclusive evidence that climate change is going to make major changes like AL Gore predicted.

column162: All fish and shellfish are temperature sensitive.  They follow patterns which include spawning and foraging.      For lobsters, the urge to spawn is great when they follow the slight rising temperature changes.  In the Spring, when they detect changes in water temperature, the females head inshore to molt.  After the females molt, the hard-shelled males show up to spawn.  The females harden up a bit, then it's time for the males to molt.  It is (was) almost predictable.      Now the soft females are fodder for the predators.  They arrive at about the same time as the males, Stripers & Dogs gorge them selves on the easy pickins.      Well, guess what, the same lobster cannot be caught twice.  If it's fish food, it won't get to the human's table, will it?  Oh, well maybe indirectly, Stripers are good to eat (for humans), right?

column162: who cares?  the fisheries are drastically more likely to be impacted by regulations created by non-fishermen based on insufficient data.  it seriously makes no difference.  this is like asking whether UV rays contributed to deterioration of a house that was destroyed by a tornado.  yes, it probably had an impact, but the impact was so infinitesimal as compared to the negative effects of the primary problem.
column163: if climate change reaches the fishery world on a fundamental basis, the range and annual patterns of migratory fish will change.  so the fisheries will not necessarily be impacted positively or negatively, however the specific fishery of a particular port will be impacted.  if the range of black sea bass extends northward, perhaps the virginia fishery would suffer, but the massachusetts fishery could improve.  at the same time, a new fishery in the virginia area may develop to take the place of the vacated black sea bass.  the question is not whether the fishery will be affected, but net impact on ports.  fishermen must be able to adapt, policy must allow for that adaptation.

column101: I’m not sure climate change has had a positive effect on our fishery, but the weather the last two springs has..  We catch Alewives in the spring, and water temperatures have a major effect on their behavior and intensity during the run.. If the water temp. spikes, the fish rush in a shorter period of time, some spawn too early and drop back out to sea. Despite the warm offshore water temperatures last couple years, the cold prolonged springs have kept our river temperatures from rising too fast suddenly, resulting in what appears to be a longer lasting steady run of Alewives for us, which has resulted in increased harvest numbers.
column157: I’m not sure if this is what you are asking exactly... but we sell Alewives for bait to lobstermen.. So if the lobster fishery is effected so is our ability to sell Alewives.   There are certainly forces outside the climate change discussion having negative impacts on the lobster industry, and those have impacted some of the guys we deal with.. that being said, the last 4-6 years we’ve had many of our “regular” customers setting gear later in the spring than in past years, due to cold water temperatures, and where we have such a small window of time to harvest Alewives some of them are not around to buy bait. We also see an increase of lobstermen switching to the Halibut fishery, and while they still buy Alewives for this, it’s in much smaller quantities..
column159: We have far more fish available in our location now than we did 30 years ago..  Our Alewife run in 1990 was 222,000 or there abouts..  2020 was around 1.3 million fish..   while improved fish passage has played an enormous role in the increase in numbers, I suspect there are other things that are having an effect as well.

column285: Licensed commercial fishermen speak for licensed commercial fishermen only, not “fishing communities” as a whole. Licensed commercial fishermen in federally-managed groundfisheries represent an even smaller number and less diverse grouping of participants. Fishing communities are comprised of a diversity of actors--  members of fishing families, participants across the entire fisheries value chain, those involved in ancillary, dockside services, and seafood consumers. In surveys like this, the perspectives of women, youth, minorities (foreign-born workers and immigrants), and indigenous people are excluded while the voices and needs of the most privileged and powerful, predominantly older white males within fishing communities are magnified.  A majority of participants in fisheries and members of fishing communities-- including the most vulnerable and adaptable-- are left out of surveys that simply poll licensed commercial fishermen.      For example, the tribal women and children who lost their commercial licenses because they are “not residents of Maine” won’t be able to share their thoughts. My friend B, a Cambodian refugee who runs a fishing fleet (formerly out of Portland, now out of Gloucester), will not be able to respond because while he may land over $1 million USD in fish a year, he does not read or write in English. You will not get a response from the people who pick and process shellfish, groundfish, and lobster. Nor will you hear from the wives of fishermen who are staying home to provide childcare and sell products direct to customers this summer due to the covid-19 outbreak. The unlicensed crew, deckhands, and sternmen won’t be able to respond.  And what about people who sell bait, run the wharves, run the seafood restaurants and markets, make the gear, fix the boats? What about the Asian women who fish for periwinkles and mackerel?  The unlicensed women and children who work onboard to cull and shuck shellfish?  Fish are a public resource and I am of the opinion that non-licensed community members also have a right to resources in the form of accessible, affordable, and nutritious seafood.  Do they also have a say in how we respond and adapt to climate change?      I completed this survey and shared my thoughts, but I sincerely hope it is not used for decision making purposes without the explicit acknowledgement that survey results only reflect the knowledge and opinions of a very small percentage of individuals situated within fishing communities.

column162: I don't feel that climate change is happening at the rate that has been reported. Not because of changing water temperature, but because sea urchins aren't there to eat the kelp. Rabbit population directly relates to coyote population. I realize that isn't the ocean, but it appears to me that these changes aren't based on major global climate change, but many factors. I do agree that we have seen minimal local changes in the world.
